You are an INDEPENDENT REVIEWER performing a STATISTICAL-INTEGRITY
PRE-REGISTRATION AUDIT of two DRAFT scientific experiment records in this
research repository. This is a data-validation and reproducibility review of a
research pipeline — it is NOT security or penetration testing. You have full
read access to the repository and should read whatever files you need to
verify the pre-registration's correctness claims. You are an independent
methodologist: not the designer, not the person who will run the experiment,
and with no stake in whether the experiment passes or fails.

BACKGROUND: this is the "NL-boundary" leg of two experiments, l3a-parse and
a5-nl. They test whether a deterministic (non-LLM) front-end parser can
recover a closed query grammar from blind, held-out natural-language phrasings
of two frozen evaluation sets (a family/world vertical and a code vertical),
compared against a measured gold-parse ceiling. A run is scored PASS or FAIL
by pre-registered Wilson-confidence-bound gates. The scoring code contains a
series of fail-closed VALIDITY CHECKS ("gates" G0-G7) whose job is to mark a
run INSTRUMENT-INVALID whenever the input data records are malformed or
internally inconsistent, so that a nominal PASS can never be reported off of
corrupt or contradictory measurements. Your review confirms those validity
checks behave as the pre-registration specifies.

REVIEW HISTORY: an earlier round of this audit (your own prior report,
committed verbatim at poc/nlb-skeptic/skeptic-round2-output.txt) confirmed
eight earlier items resolved and identified exactly THREE remaining
freeze-blocking correctness gaps in the validity checks:

  (i)   "G0 supersede path not executable in kot-log/1" — the retry-recovery
        mechanism (a later successful run row replacing an earlier successful
        run row of the same experiment arm) was described in the scorer but
        could not actually exist in a real log line: the log schema had no
        `supersedes` property (additionalProperties:false), and the official
        event:"supersede" mechanism only annotates non-"ok" rows while the
        scorer only consumes "ok" rows. The raw check also accepted a
        dictionary-valued `supersedes` and a same-run cross-arm reference.
  (ii)  "Instrument run body not directly loggable" — the pinned instrument's
        emitted run body carried a top-level `"arm"` key the log schema
        rejects and omitted event/exit/prereg_hash that the log writer
        requires, so the advertised raw output could not be appended to the
        real log without an undocumented hand transform.
  (iii) "G1 counts-integrity incomplete" — the counts check did not require
        the per-control-family acceptable-refusal counts to sum to the
        run-level acceptable total, and accepted non-integer totals
        (n_covered / n_control / dev_n as floats) and an out-of-range
        dev_parse_refused, so an internally inconsistent or non-integral set
        of measurements could still report a nominal PASS.

plus two lower-severity items (two register entries ASM-0422/ASM-0425 still
citing superseded 27/33 and 9/27 figures; an instrument docstring still
describing a byte-identical engine) and one cosmetic nit (an n=527 Wilson
"complement form" claimed bit-identical but actually one floating-point ULP
off at 4/527, with no effect on any pass/fail decision).

The designer has recorded remediations for all of these in
docs/design-nl-boundary-l3a-parse-a5-nl.md section 14.9 ("Independent-skeptic
