172:{"id": "ASM-0622", "tag": "STIPULATED", "claim": "NLB l3a audit r1 protocol, CORRECTED-COUNT SUCCESSOR of ASM-0422 (supersede-by-citation; the ASM-0422 line stands as append-only history and is no longer cited by the l3a-parse/a5-nl records): the protocol is unchanged - (i) mechanically re-score the COMMITTED judge transcript (sha256 7f3f2291a7e46fb554e7477fc92ff3611d4a0131e117aa5c027960563f36fb1a) restricted to the in-scope covered sampled items, (ii) top the covered-only sample to 60 via a FRESH judge identity given ONLY new in-scope items (same pinned prompt-audit.md, same deterministic sample rule over the 7 in-scope families, already-judged qids skipped), no item ever judged twice, original audit artifact never overwritten - but the provenance arithmetic in ASM-0422's rationale was wrong: the original committed audit sample contains 28 (not 27) in-scope covered items, so r1 = 28 mechanically re-scored + 32 (not 33) fresh-judge items. The 60/60 r1 gate result is unchanged.", "backing_ref": "data/nlb-phrasings-l3a/audit-recoverability-r1.json sha256 57e9d8d12826ae6ba28da4289fcc703109b2fb9994ef99eb589655874ea6da6d; original audit sha256 d6365bd95e7d61a1cce7585bb446aa8f905b2b8eec08d0756a446e2e70a09bf5; tools/experiments/nlb/EVAL-BUILD-SPEC.md step 5", "rationale": "The round-2 independent skeptic held (correctly) that an append-only register still CITED by live records must carry a mechanical superseding correction, not a prose disclaimer in the design doc: the 27+33 arithmetic in ASM-0422's rationale contradicts the committed r1 artifact (28 rescored + 32 fresh). This successor restates the identical no-re-roll protocol with the artifact's counts; both records now cite ASM-0622 in place of ASM-0422. Revisit condition: none for this pair; a successor audit protocol supersedes it with its own ASM.", "load_bearing": true, "status": "open", "owner": "designer-1", "date": "2026-07-10"}
173:{"id": "ASM-0623", "tag": "EXTRAPOLATION", "claim": "Sizing/expectation note only, CORRECTED-COUNT SUCCESSOR of ASM-0425 (supersede-by-citation; the ASM-0425 line stands as append-only history and is no longer cited by the l3a-parse/a5-nl records): the l3a-parse primary planning value 0.95 is implausible - the audit sample measured natural-synonym phrasing on 9/28 = 0.3214 (not 9/27 = 0.333; the in-scope covered sample has 28 items per the committed r1 artifact) of in-scope covered sampled items (count-maker 4/4, part-lookup 4/4, instance-true 1/4), and against the single-label mapper lexicon (no synonym table) those items are expected to abstain, putting the covered-exact rate plausibly in or below the 463-485/527 INCONCLUSIVE band (extrapolated from a 28-item audit sample to the 527-item scored set and from judge label-use to mapper parse behaviour - neither measured end-to-end). Used ONLY to set maintainer expectations that an INCONCLUSIVE/FAIL landing is live; never a premise for any gate, re-authoring, or re-design; the re-scope keeps every synonym-phrased item scored.", "backing_ref": "data/nlb-phrasings-l3a/audit-recoverability-r1.json sha256 57e9d8d12826ae6ba28da4289fcc703109b2fb9994ef99eb589655874ea6da6d; docs/design-nl-boundary-l3a-parse-a5-nl.md sections 14.3 and 14.9", "load_bearing": false, "status": "open", "owner": "designer-1", "date": "2026-07-10", "resolution_path": "The l3a-parse run measures the covered-exact rate and the label-verbatim vs paraphrase stratification directly; whatever it returns supersedes this band. An INCONCLUSIVE landing re-opens FK-NLB-2 with data per ASM-0141; a FAIL routes to parser investment per the frozen kill text."}
174:{"id": "ASM-0624", "tag": "STIPULATED", "claim": "NLB skeptic round-2 RE-AUDIT remediation (extends ASM-0621's lawful edit set by exactly this named, diff-scoped edit set and no other; SUPERSEDES ASM-0621 item (1)'s supersede mechanics, which the re-audit proved unexecutable in a kot-log/1 log): (1) kot-log/1 gains an executable run-row retry-supersession channel - a run row may carry supersedes:[row sha256,...], row identity = sha256 of the replaced results-log line's exact bytes incl. newline (identical to prev_sha256 / reuse.row_hashes identity); log-append enforces fail-closed: run-event only, mandatory non-empty reason, no duplicate targets, every target an EXISTING exit:'ok' run row of the SAME config.arm and phase not already superseded; self/forward/cyclic references are structurally impossible (a target must already be a chain line); event:'supersede' keeps refusing exit:'ok' targets, so a success is never voided WITHOUT its replacement row, and any retry remains in-chain and auditor-visible (result-shopping is additionally detectable via gate G6 determinism). (2) Both pinned scorers' G0 re-verify the SAME semantics independently: supersedes must be a non-empty list of distinct 64-hex row hashes, targets present among scored records, same-arm, non-self; malformed forms (dict/string), cross-arm supersession, byte-duplicate rows, records without a string config.arm (the top-level arm fallback is removed), dangling targets, arms with zero survivors, and >1 surviving row per arm are all INSTRUMENT-INVALID in every log order; verdict-gen passes eligible rows (including retry-superseded ok rows) unchanged to the pinned scorer, which is the resolution point. (3) The pinned instrument emits a DIRECTLY appendable kot-log/1 run body: event 'run', exit 'ok', phase from --phase, prereg_hash auto-stamped from registry/frozen-index.json post-freeze (absent pre-freeze so log-append refuses ERR_P2_NOT_FROZEN), no undeclared top-level key (the former top-level 'arm' is removed; config.arm is the only arm declaration), and native --supersedes/--reason flags for the retry path. (4) G1/G2/G4 counts hardening in both scorers: per-family control acceptable ('ok') sums must equal the run-level n_control_refused_acceptable; run-level totals n_covered/n_control/dev_n, dev_parse_refused, and every gold-replication counter must be strict non-negative integers; dev_parse_refused <= dev_n; G4 divides only well-formed in-range counters. (5) Honesty corrections carried in the same change: the instrument docstring no longer claims a byte-identical engine (G2 behavioural claim restated), and the section-14.8 item-7 'bit-equal' complement claim is softened to the measured fact (identical gate decision at every integer count; 4/527 differs by one binary64 ULP, 9/855 bit-equal). All edits are log-schema/log-writer/scorer/instrument-envelope side; no phrasing or eval byte, endpoint, threshold, decision boundary, or planned n moves.", "backing_ref": "docs/design-nl-boundary-l3a-parse-a5-nl.md section 14.9; poc/nlb-skeptic/skeptic-round2-output.txt sha256 6e60f408a4231c595832dd6b91262ef49c3617a410e5e71522ea33bb578b7773 (attacks on the dict-valued and cross-arm supersedes, zeroed control-family ok, float totals and dev_parse_refused reproduced there); analysis/l3a_parse.py + analysis/a5_nl.py --selftest fixtures on each reproduced attack; scratch-log run-to-log integration demonstration via the real tools/registry/log-append.py", "rationale": "The round-2 re-audit proved the registered recovery path could not exist in a real hash-chained log (kot-log/1 additionalProperties:false rejects the field; log-append's supersede event cannot target ok rows; only ok rows reach the scorer), so freezing would have pinned an unexecutable protocol where one accidental duplicate append poisons the record permanently. Making the channel real in schema+writer+scorer, with append-time AND read-time enforcement of one registered rule, converts the promise into an executable, auditable mechanism while PRESERVING the anti-re-roll invariant (a successful row is only ever replaced by an explicit, reasoned, same-arm successor in the chain). The counts hardening closes the reproduced acceptance of contradictory control-family classifications and non-integral counters. Revisit condition: any change to kot-log/1 row identity or to canonical JSON serialization must re-derive the scorer's self-contained _row_sha twin.", "load_bearing": true, "status": "open", "owner": "designer-1", "date": "2026-07-10"}

codex
The append writer’s enforcement is sound on the requested retry attacks, including forward/cycle precursors and the legacy `event:"supersede"` invariant. The remaining question is scorer classification after eligibility; I’ve confirmed the raw G0 omissions are reachable for a schema-valid, correctly hash-chained line if the chain is not produced by the designated writer, because verdict generation chain-checks but does not revalidate log schema/append semantics. I’m completing pin/freezability and Wilson checks before assigning severity.
