registry/assumptions.jsonl:1:{"id": "ASM-0001", "claim": "Kernel-expressibility coverage of the pinned TinyStories task-family corpus (1,709,765 tokens, corpus pin b6bcc9f6) is 0.3542 at rung molecules-v0, 0.2210 at rung kernel-v0, 0.7841 at the wn31-aligned band \u2014 measured 2026-07-08 on the INCOMPLETE kernel-v0 + molecules-v0 instance as it existed that day. The number is corpus-indexed, rung-indexed, and kernel-state-indexed: per the verdict's extrapolation envelope it extrapolates to NO other corpus, rung, or kernel state, and is re-measured as the kernel grows.", "tag": "MEASURED", "backing_ref": "registry/verdicts/m0b.json sha256 da475e98744ffe1dc635d2aa814c1955a120cef6b93dedef771af9d087fb7f0d; analysis-output sha256 63ce6485; audit CONFIRMED registry/audits/m0b/1-gate-a-codex.json", "load_bearing": true, "status": "resolved", "owner": "writer-1", "date": "2026-07-09", "notes": "CORRECTION ENTRY: this claim had been narrated in programme discussion as the kernel's 'natural coverage' (a general property). That framing strips all three indices and was an unlicensed EXTRAPOLATION stated as fact \u2014 the motivating incident for this register (docs/next/assumption-register.md section 7). Doc-level fixes applied 2026-07-09 in docs/next/arch-survey.md and docs/next/00-programme-2-overview.md."}
registry/assumptions.jsonl:2:{"id": "ASM-0002", "claim": "A coverage level of roughly 0.35 would also hold on corpora other than the pinned TinyStories task family (e.g. the D-EXT external slice, general web text, or any later eval corpus).", "tag": "EXTRAPOLATION", "backing_ref": "", "load_bearing": false, "status": "open", "owner": "writer-1", "date": "2026-07-09", "resolution_path": "Re-run the m0b census machinery (tools/experiments/m0b_instrument.py, deterministic, ~$0 on-box) on each new corpus BEFORE any design cites a coverage number for it or powers a covered-slice test on it. Live warning that this projection is doubtful: the f2 external slice showed zero item flips on D-EXT (registry/verdicts/f2.json sha256 38422b3c...) \u2014 in-house-slice behaviour did not transfer, and D-EXT lemma coverage is an open diagnosis question in the F2 post-mortem.", "notes": "Filed as the open counterpart of ASM-0001: the exact projection the 'natural coverage' narration silently asserted. May motivate queueing a census run; may not premise any decision while open."}
registry/assumptions.jsonl:21:{"id": "ASM-0019", "claim": "The WiC / definitional-MMLU kappa_B yield of the define-op is a projection, not a measured quantity: the substrate is biomedical (GO/PO) and WiC is general-vocabulary, so the define-checkable yield may be small or ~0.", "tag": "EXTRAPOLATION", "backing_ref": "docs/design-kot-query-define-op.md §4 / §7.2 / §7.3", "load_bearing": false, "status": "open", "owner": "designer-1", "date": "2026-07-09", "resolution_path": "The b-cov census re-run (docs/design-kot-query-define-op.md §7.2 / docs/next/architecture-ladder.md §10.1, Tier 0, ~$0, CPU-only) measures kappa_B^engine for gold-parse and mapper-parse before/after the op lands; the measured delta converts this projection. NEVER a premise for building the op or any downstream claim.", "notes": "define-op EXTRAPOLATION (memo ASM-DEF-5); non-load-bearing, resolved by the census."}
registry/assumptions.jsonl:23:{"backing_ref": "poc/f2b-transfer/llmproxy-design.md S2/S3/S6; registry/experiments/f2b-transfer-llmproxy.json envelope clauses 2 and 5", "claim": "Kernel-tradition familiarity of LLM judges: NSM literature and NSM-style explications are plausibly in GPT-5.x training data, so an LLM filling the judge-1 role may endorse a familiar explication STYLE rather than judge content from concept competence, biasing the f2b-transfer-llmproxy endorsement statistic A_1p in an unproven direction (plausibly upward). Kernel-INSTANCE-naivety is enforced by E5 context control; kernel-TRADITION-naivety cannot be.", "date": "2026-07-09", "id": "ASM-0021", "load_bearing": false, "notes": "f2b-transfer-llmproxy design (judge-1 LLM stand-in); asymmetric-reading clause depends on the PLAUSIBILITY not the truth of the upward direction.", "owner": "designer-1", "resolution_path": "Run the human-judged f2b-transfer stage-1 (the frozen record's own path) and compare its A against A_1p on the identical 360 items: the difference measures the LLM-judge bias directly. Interim bound: the deranged-gloss probe gate (false-endorsement point-rate >= 0.30 invalidates) bounds the crudest style-endorsement form. NEVER a premise: the llmproxy envelope caps any PASS at weak-feasibility-proxy independent of this entry.", "status": "open", "tag": "EXTRAPOLATION"}
registry/assumptions.jsonl:26:{"id": "ASM-0024", "claim": "The back-patch rescuable fraction measured on general 2-hop factual queries (up to 66%, arXiv:2406.12775) extends at useful magnitude to the nsk1 kernel-covered synthetic 2-hop slices at R1-R2 (SmolLM2-135M/360M).", "tag": "EXTRAPOLATION", "backing_ref": "arXiv:2406.12775 (2024); reports/lit-structured-parsing-and-inner-symbolic.md B5", "load_bearing": false, "status": "open", "owner": "designer-1", "date": "2026-07-10", "resolution_path": "nsk1 Stage-0 measures the rescuable fraction directly on the covered slice; the pre-declared floor (Wilson-LB >= 0.15 over swept failures) converts this into a family-level cheap kill"}
registry/assumptions.jsonl:27:{"id": "ASM-0025", "claim": "Function-vector / contrastive-activation-addition steering effects, measured at task granularity in the literature, are extractable and causally effective at ENTITY/CONCEPT granularity (one cached vector per world-entity, exact-hash addressed) on SmolLM2-135M/360M.", "tag": "EXTRAPOLATION", "backing_ref": "arXiv:2310.15213 (2024); arXiv:2312.06681 (2023); reliability caveat arXiv:2410.17245 (2024)", "load_bearing": false, "status": "open", "owner": "designer-1", "date": "2026-07-10", "resolution_path": "nsk1 Stage-1 calibration split measures per-entity steering-cache validity (cache-extraction gate) before the final campaign; failure of the gate falls back to the kernel-gated activation-modulation channel (FK-NSK-1 option b) or kills the write channel"}
